==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swaddle
<hw>Swad"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>swe<?/il</ets>, <ets>swe<?/el</ets>, fr. <ets>swe<?/ain</ets> to
bind. See <er>Swathe</er>.]</ety> <def>Anything used to swaddle with, as
a cloth or band; a swaddling band.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They put me in bed in all my swaddles.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swaddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swaddle
<hw>Swad"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Swaddled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swaddling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
bind as with a bandage; to bind or warp tightly with clothes; to swathe;
-- used esp. of infants; <as>as, to <ex>swaddle</ex> a
baby</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>swaddled</qex> me up in my nightgown with long pieces of
linen.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To beat; to cudgel.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swaddlebill</ent>⟦br⟧
